ed around the 213.30\u2013213.60 region \u2014 a zone that accumulated six prior touches and acted as a meaningful base. From there, a measured grind higher developed through early July before the pace accelerated sharply on 6 July, when price broke above 217.00 on a wide-range daily candle. The 15 July session then delivered the most significant single-day advance in the dataset, printing a high of 219.62 and closing at 219.61 \u2014 a move that established fresh near-term highs. Since that spike, the pair has been pulling back in a controlled manner, with daily candles printing progressively tighter ranges between roughly 218.05 and 218.93. This compression, occurring well above the 215.57 prior reaction zone, is consistent with a healthy consolidation within a bullish trend rather than a distribution top. The 214.65 zone beneath that adds a further layer of structural support, and the distance between current price and those levels suggests the market is not under immediate pressure from below.\n\nThe H1 picture reinforces this read. Over the past 24 hours, price has been oscillating in an exceptionally narrow corridor, broadly between 218.04 and 218.38. There has been no meaningful directional conviction on the hourly timeframe \u2014 a classic coiling dynamic. The slight uptick in the most recent hours, with the 12:00 candle nudging toward 218.35, hints at tentative demand returning, though it would take a clear break above the 218.55\u2013218.60 area to suggest the intraday range is resolving to the upside.\n\nThe calendar is empty today, which removes the prospect of scheduled volatility catalysts. In the absence of data, price action is likely to remain technically driven, and the current consolidation may simply extend further into the week. Quiet sessions can occasionally produce false breaks of intraday ranges, so the tight band between 218.05 and 218.55 warrants close attention as a potential coil.\n\nThe bullish read would come under question if price were to break and close on the daily chart below the 217.50 area \u2014 the lower boundary of the post-spike consolidation \u2014 and more decisively so below 216.40, which marked the intraday low during the 8 July advance. A sustained move beneath those levels would suggest the 219.62 high represented a near-term exhaustion point rather than a platform for further gains.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}